001.Black_footed_Albatross.description: A large seabird with dark brown to black plumage, white around the base of the bill and under the eye. Has a large wingspan and is an excellent glider.
001.Black_footed_Albatross.habitat: Pelagic (open ocean), breeds on remote islands
001.Black_footed_Albatross.distribution: North Pacific Ocean, breeds on Hawaiian Islands, Japan, and other Pacific islands
001.Black_footed_Albatross.size: Length: 68-74 cm, Wingspan: 193-216 cm, Weight: 2.5-4.3 kg
001.Black_footed_Albatross.diet: Fish, squid, crustaceans, and other marine life. Also scavenges on carrion.
001.Black_footed_Albatross.behavior: Spends most of its life at sea, only coming to land to breed. Excellent glider, can travel thousands of kilometers. Forms large breeding colonies.

002.Laysan_Albatross.description: Large seabird with white head and body, dark back and wings. Has distinctive dark eye patch.
002.Laysan_Albatross.habitat: Pelagic (open ocean), breeds on remote islands
002.Laysan_Albatross.distribution: North Pacific Ocean, breeds on Hawaiian Islands and other Pacific islands
002.Laysan_Albatross.size: Length: 71-79 cm, Wingspan: 195-203 cm, Weight: 2.4-4.1 kg
002.Laysan_Albatross.diet: Squid, fish, crustaceans, and other marine life
002.Laysan_Albatross.behavior: Spends most of life at sea. Returns to land only to breed. Forms large colonies. Long-lived, can live 40+ years.

003.Sooty_Albatross.description: Large seabird with dark sooty-brown to blackish plumage. Has white crescent behind eye.
003.Sooty_Albatross.habitat: Pelagic (open ocean), breeds on remote islands
003.Sooty_Albatross.distribution: Southern Ocean, breeds on subantarctic islands
003.Sooty_Albatross.size: Length: 84-89 cm, Wingspan: 200-213 cm, Weight: 2.5-3.5 kg
003.Sooty_Albatross.diet: Squid, fish, and other marine life
003.Sooty_Albatross.behavior: Spends most of life at sea. Excellent glider. Forms breeding colonies on remote islands.

004.Groove_billed_Ani.description: Large black bird with long tail, grooved bill, and iridescent black plumage.
004.Groove_billed_Ani.habitat: Open grasslands, agricultural areas, and scrublands
004.Groove_billed_Ani.distribution: Southern United States, Mexico, Central America, and northern South America
004.Groove_billed_Ani.behavior: Social, forms groups. Cooperative breeding. Communal nesting.

005.Crested_Auklet.description: Small seabird with black body, white belly, and distinctive forward-curving crest on forehead.
005.Crested_Auklet.distribution: North Pacific, from Alaska to Japan
005.Crested_Auklet.size: Length: 18-27 cm, Wingspan: 40-50 cm, Weight: 195-330 g
005.Crested_Auklet.diet: Small fish, krill, and other marine invertebrates
005.Crested_Auklet.behavior: Forms large breeding colonies. Dives for food. Nocturnal at breeding sites.

006.Least_Auklet.description: Very small seabird, smallest auklet. Black above, white below, with white facial plumes in breeding season.
006.Least_Auklet.distribution: North Pacific, from Alaska to Japan
006.Least_Auklet.size: Length: 14-18 cm, Wingspan: 35-40 cm, Weight: 75-100 g
006.Least_Auklet.diet: Small zooplankton, krill, and small fish
006.Least_Auklet.behavior: Forms huge breeding colonies. Very social. Dives for food.

007.Parakeet_Auklet.description: Small seabird with dark gray body, white belly, and distinctive upturned red bill.
007.Parakeet_Auklet.distribution: North Pacific, from Alaska to Japan
007.Parakeet_Auklet.size: Length: 23-25 cm, Wingspan: 40-45 cm, Weight: 200-300 g
007.Parakeet_Auklet.behavior: Forms breeding colonies. Dives for food. Nocturnal at breeding sites.

008.Rhinoceros_Auklet.description: Medium-sized seabird with dark gray-brown body, white belly, and distinctive horn-like projection on bill during breeding.
008.Rhinoceros_Auklet.distribution: North Pacific, from Alaska to California and Japan
008.Rhinoceros_Auklet.size: Length: 30-35 cm, Wingspan: 60-70 cm, Weight: 350-500 g
008.Rhinoceros_Auklet.diet: Small fish, especially sand lance and herring
008.Rhinoceros_Auklet.behavior: Forms breeding colonies. Nocturnal at breeding sites. Dives for food.

009.Brewer_Blackbird.description: Medium-sized blackbird. Males are black with purple-blue iridescence. Females are brown with dark eyes.
009.Brewer_Blackbird.habitat: Open areas, fields, parks, and urban areas
009.Brewer_Blackbird.distribution: Western North America, from Canada to Mexico
009.Brewer_Blackbird.size: Length: 20-25 cm, Wingspan: 36-40 cm, Weight: 60-90 g
009.Brewer_Blackbird.behavior: Forms flocks. Nests in colonies. Year-round resident in many areas.

010.Red_winged_Blackbird.description: Medium-sized blackbird. Males are black with red and yellow shoulder patches. Females are streaked brown and black.
010.Red_winged_Blackbird.habitat: Marshes, wetlands, fields, and agricultural areas
010.Red_winged_Blackbird.distribution: Throughout North America, from Alaska to Central America
010.Red_winged_Blackbird.size: Length: 17-23 cm, Wingspan: 31-40 cm, Weight: 41-65 g
010.Red_winged_Blackbird.diet: Seeds, grains, insects, and small vertebrates
010.Red_winged_Blackbird.behavior: Forms large flocks, especially in winter. Males defend breeding territories aggressively. Migratory in northern range.

011.Rusty_Blackbird.description: Medium-sized blackbird. Breeding males are black with greenish iridescence. Females are brown with rusty edges.
011.Rusty_Blackbird.distribution: North America, breeds in Canada and Alaska, winters in southeastern United States
011.Rusty_Blackbird.size: Length: 22-25 cm, Wingspan: 36-40 cm, Weight: 60-70 g
011.Rusty_Blackbird.diet: Insects, seeds, and small aquatic animals
011.Rusty_Blackbird.behavior: Migratory. Declining population. Nests in coniferous forests near water.

012.Yellow_headed_Blackbird.description: Medium-sized blackbird. Males are black with bright yellow head and chest. Females are brown with yellow throat.
012.Yellow_headed_Blackbird.distribution: Western and central North America, winters in southwestern United States and Mexico
012.Yellow_headed_Blackbird.size: Length: 20-26 cm, Wingspan: 36-42 cm, Weight: 60-100 g
012.Yellow_headed_Blackbird.behavior: Migratory. Forms large flocks. Males are polygamous. Nests in colonies in marshes.

013.Bobolink.description: Medium-sized songbird. Breeding males are black with white back and yellow nape. Females and winter males are streaked brown.
013.Bobolink.distribution: North America, breeds in northern United States and Canada, winters in South America
013.Bobolink.size: Length: 16-18 cm, Wingspan: 25-28 cm, Weight: 30-50 g
013.Bobolink.behavior: Long-distance migrant. Forms large flocks. Males perform flight displays during breeding.

014.Indigo_Bunting.description: Small songbird. Breeding males are brilliant blue all over. Females and winter males are brown with blue tinges.
014.Indigo_Bunting.habitat: Brushy areas, forest edges, and open woodlands
014.Indigo_Bunting.distribution: Eastern and central North America, winters in Central America and Caribbean
014.Indigo_Bunting.size: Length: 11-13 cm, Wingspan: 18-23 cm, Weight: 12-18 g
014.Indigo_Bunting.diet: Seeds, insects, and berries. Eats small seeds and insects during breeding season.
014.Indigo_Bunting.behavior: Migratory. Males sing from high perches. Nests in dense shrubs.

015.Lazuli_Bunting.description: Small songbird. Males have bright blue head and back, orange breast, white belly. Females are brown with blue tinges.
015.Lazuli_Bunting.habitat: Brushy areas, open woodlands, and streamside thickets
015.Lazuli_Bunting.distribution: Western North America, from Canada to Mexico
015.Lazuli_Bunting.size: Length: 13-14 cm, Wingspan: 21-23 cm, Weight: 13-18 g
015.Lazuli_Bunting.behavior: Migratory. Males sing from exposed perches. Forms small flocks in winter.

016.Painted_Bunting.description: Small, colorful songbird. Males are brightly colored with blue head, green back, red underparts. Females are green above, yellow-green below.
016.Painted_Bunting.habitat: Brushy areas, woodland edges, and gardens
016.Painted_Bunting.distribution: Southeastern United States and Mexico, winters in Central America
016.Painted_Bunting.size: Length: 12-13 cm, Wingspan: 21-23 cm, Weight: 13-19 g
016.Painted_Bunting.behavior: Migratory. Shy and secretive. Males are territorial during breeding season.

017.Cardinal.description: Medium-sized songbird. Males are bright red with black face mask and crested head. Females are brown with red tinges.
017.Cardinal.distribution: Eastern and central North America, from Canada to Mexico
017.Cardinal.size: Length: 21-24 cm, Wingspan: 25-31 cm, Weight: 33-65 g
017.Cardinal.behavior: Year-round resident. Visits bird feeders. Sings beautiful song. Pairs stay together year-round.

018.Spotted_Catbird.description: Medium-sized bird with olive-green plumage and white spots. Has distinctive cat-like call.
018.Spotted_Catbird.behavior: Territorial, builds large stick nests. Known for cat-like mewing calls.

019.Gray_Catbird.description: Medium-sized songbird. Slate gray overall with black cap and chestnut undertail coverts.
019.Gray_Catbird.habitat: Dense thickets, shrublands, gardens, and parks
019.Gray_Catbird.distribution: Eastern and central North America, winters in southeastern United States, Mexico, and Central America
019.Gray_Catbird.size: Length: 20-24 cm, Wingspan: 22-30 cm, Weight: 23-56 g
019.Gray_Catbird.behavior: Mimics other birds. Skulks in dense vegetation. Migratory in northern range.

020.Yellow_breasted_Chat.description: Large warbler with bright yellow breast, olive-green back, white spectacles, and long tail.
020.Yellow_breasted_Chat.habitat: Dense thickets, brushy areas, and woodland edges
020.Yellow_breasted_Chat.distribution: North America, breeds in United States and southern Canada, winters in Central America
020.Yellow_breasted_Chat.size: Length: 17-19 cm, Wingspan: 23-27 cm, Weight: 20-34 g
020.Yellow_breasted_Chat.behavior: Largest North American warbler. Skulks in dense vegetation. Mimics other birds.

021.Eastern_Towhee.description: Large sparrow. Males are black above with white spots, rufous sides, and white belly. Females are brown where males are black.
021.Eastern_Towhee.habitat: Brushy areas, forest edges, and thickets
021.Eastern_Towhee.distribution: Eastern North America, from Canada to Gulf Coast
021.Eastern_Towhee.size: Length: 17-21 cm, Wingspan: 20-30 cm, Weight: 32-53 g
021.Eastern_Towhee.behavior: Forages on ground by scratching. Sings 'drink-your-tea' song. Year-round resident in south.

022.Chuck_will_Widow.description: Large nightjar with mottled brown and gray plumage, large eyes, and wide mouth.
022.Chuck_will_Widow.distribution: Southeastern United States, winters in Central America and Caribbean
022.Chuck_will_Widow.size: Length: 28-33 cm, Wingspan: 58-66 cm, Weight: 65-100 g
022.Chuck_will_Widow.diet: Flying insects and small birds caught at night
022.Chuck_will_Widow.behavior: Migratory. Nocturnal. Sings 'chuck-will's-widow' song at night. Nests on ground.

023.Brandt_Cormorant.description: Large seabird with black body, blue throat patch in breeding season, and long tail.
023.Brandt_Cormorant.distribution: Pacific Coast of North America, from Alaska to Baja California
023.Brandt_Cormorant.size: Length: 81-91 cm, Wingspan: 122-137 cm, Weight: 1.4-2.5 kg
023.Brandt_Cormorant.behavior: Year-round resident. Dives for fish. Nests in colonies on cliffs.

024.Red_faced_Cormorant.description: Large seabird with black body, red face in breeding season, and white flank patches.
024.Red_faced_Cormorant.distribution: North Pacific, from Alaska to Japan
024.Red_faced_Cormorant.size: Length: 71-79 cm, Wingspan: 110-122 cm, Weight: 1.2-2.0 kg
024.Red_faced_Cormorant.behavior: Year-round resident. Dives for fish. Nests in colonies on cliffs.

025.Pelagic_Cormorant.description: Medium-sized seabird with black body, white flank patches, and red face in breeding season.
025.Pelagic_Cormorant.distribution: North Pacific, from Alaska to California
025.Pelagic_Cormorant.size: Length: 64-89 cm, Wingspan: 100-120 cm, Weight: 1.2-2.3 kg
025.Pelagic_Cormorant.behavior: Year-round resident. Dives for fish. Nests in colonies on cliffs.

026.Bronzed_Cowbird.description: Medium-sized blackbird. Males are black with bronzy iridescence and red eyes. Females are brown.
026.Bronzed_Cowbird.habitat: Open areas, grasslands, and agricultural fields
026.Bronzed_Cowbird.distribution: Southwestern United States, Mexico, and Central America
026.Bronzed_Cowbird.size: Length: 20-23 cm, Wingspan: 32-36 cm, Weight: 50-70 g
026.Bronzed_Cowbird.behavior: Brood parasite. Lays eggs in other birds' nests. Year-round resident in many areas.

027.Shiny_Cowbird.description: Small blackbird. Males are black with purple-blue iridescence. Females are brown.
027.Shiny_Cowbird.habitat: Open areas, grasslands, and agricultural fields
027.Shiny_Cowbird.distribution: South America, introduced to Caribbean and Florida
027.Shiny_Cowbird.size: Length: 18-22 cm, Wingspan: 30-35 cm, Weight: 30-50 g
027.Shiny_Cowbird.behavior: Brood parasite. Lays eggs in other birds' nests. Forms flocks.

028.Brown_Creeper.description: Small bird with brown mottled upperparts, white underparts, and curved bill. Climbs up tree trunks.
028.Brown_Creeper.distribution: North America, breeds in Canada and United States, winters throughout United States
028.Brown_Creeper.size: Length: 12-14 cm, Wingspan: 17-20 cm, Weight: 5-10 g
028.Brown_Creeper.behavior: Migratory in northern range. Climbs up tree trunks in spiral pattern. Nests behind loose bark.

029.American_Crow.description: Large, all-black bird with thick bill and fan-shaped tail.
029.American_Crow.habitat: Various habitats including forests, fields, and urban areas
029.American_Crow.distribution: North America, from Canada to Mexico
029.American_Crow.size: Length: 40-50 cm, Wingspan: 85-100 cm, Weight: 300-600 g
029.American_Crow.diet: Omnivorous. Eats carrion, insects, fruits, seeds, and human food waste
029.American_Crow.behavior: Highly intelligent. Forms large flocks. Uses tools. Year-round resident.

030.Fish_Crow.description: Medium-sized, all-black bird similar to American Crow but smaller with higher-pitched call.
030.Fish_Crow.distribution: Eastern and southeastern United States, year-round resident
030.Fish_Crow.size: Length: 36-40 cm, Wingspan: 75-90 cm, Weight: 200-300 g
030.Fish_Crow.diet: Fish, carrion, eggs, and human food waste
030.Fish_Crow.behavior: Year-round resident. Forms flocks. Often near water.

031.Black_billed_Cuckoo.description: Medium-sized bird with brown upperparts, white underparts, and long tail with white spots.
031.Black_billed_Cuckoo.distribution: Eastern and central North America, breeds in United States and Canada, winters in South America
031.Black_billed_Cuckoo.size: Length: 28-31 cm, Wingspan: 38-42 cm, Weight: 40-65 g
031.Black_billed_Cuckoo.behavior: Migratory. Secretive. Eats hairy caterpillars that other birds avoid.

032.Mangrove_Cuckoo.description: Medium-sized bird with brown upperparts, buff underparts, and long tail with white spots.
032.Mangrove_Cuckoo.distribution: Southern Florida, Caribbean, and Central America
032.Mangrove_Cuckoo.size: Length: 28-33 cm, Wingspan: 38-42 cm, Weight: 60-80 g
032.Mangrove_Cuckoo.behavior: Year-round resident in many areas. Secretive. Nests in trees.

033.Yellow_billed_Cuckoo.description: Medium-sized bird with brown upperparts, white underparts, and long tail with large white spots.
033.Yellow_billed_Cuckoo.habitat: Deciduous woodlands, thickets, and riparian areas
033.Yellow_billed_Cuckoo.distribution: North America, breeds in United States and Canada, winters in South America
033.Yellow_billed_Cuckoo.size: Length: 26-30 cm, Wingspan: 38-44 cm, Weight: 55-65 g
033.Yellow_billed_Cuckoo.behavior: Migratory. Secretive. Eats large numbers of caterpillars.

034.Gray_crowned_Rosy_Finch.description: Medium-sized finch with gray crown, brown body, and pink patches on wings and rump. Bill is yellow in summer, dark in winter.
034.Gray_crowned_Rosy_Finch.habitat: Alpine and subalpine areas, rocky slopes, and tundra
034.Gray_crowned_Rosy_Finch.distribution: Western North America, from Alaska to California and Rocky Mountains
034.Gray_crowned_Rosy_Finch.size: Length: 14-16 cm, Wingspan: 33 cm, Weight: 22-60 g
034.Gray_crowned_Rosy_Finch.diet: Seeds, insects, and berries. Forages on ground and in snow.
034.Gray_crowned_Rosy_Finch.behavior: Forms large flocks in winter. Breeds at high elevations. Hardy, survives in harsh mountain conditions.

035.Purple_Finch.description: Medium-sized finch. Males are raspberry-red on head, breast, and back. Females are streaked brown with white eyebrow.
035.Purple_Finch.habitat: Coniferous and mixed forests, parks, and gardens
035.Purple_Finch.distribution: North America, from Canada to southern United States
035.Purple_Finch.size: Length: 12-16 cm, Wingspan: 22-26 cm, Weight: 18-32 g
035.Purple_Finch.diet: Seeds, buds, fruits, and insects. Eats sunflower seeds at feeders.
035.Purple_Finch.behavior: Migratory in northern range, resident in south. Visits bird feeders, especially in winter.

036.Northern_Flicker.description: Large woodpecker. Brown with black bars, white rump, and yellow or red under wings. Has black crescent on chest.
036.Northern_Flicker.habitat: Open woodlands, parks, and suburban areas
036.Northern_Flicker.size: Length: 28-31 cm, Wingspan: 42-51 cm, Weight: 110-160 g
036.Northern_Flicker.diet: Ants, beetles, fruits, and seeds. Often forages on ground.
036.Northern_Flicker.behavior: Drums on trees and metal objects. Migratory in northern range. Nests in tree cavities.

037.Acadian_Flycatcher.description: Small flycatcher with olive-green upperparts, white underparts, and two white wing bars.
037.Acadian_Flycatcher.habitat: Mature deciduous forests, especially near streams
037.Acadian_Flycatcher.distribution: Eastern North America, winters in Central and South America
037.Acadian_Flycatcher.size: Length: 13-15 cm, Wingspan: 21-24 cm, Weight: 12-14 g
037.Acadian_Flycatcher.behavior: Migratory. Sits on perch and sallies out to catch insects. Builds hanging nest.

038.Great_Crested_Flycatcher.description: Large flycatcher with gray head, olive-brown back, yellow belly, and rufous tail.
038.Great_Crested_Flycatcher.distribution: Eastern North America, winters in Central and South America
038.Great_Crested_Flycatcher.size: Length: 17-21 cm, Wingspan: 34 cm, Weight: 27-40 g
038.Great_Crested_Flycatcher.behavior: Migratory. Nests in tree cavities, often uses snake skins in nest. Loud 'wheep' call.

039.Least_Flycatcher.description: Small flycatcher with olive-gray upperparts, white underparts, and two white wing bars.
039.Least_Flycatcher.distribution: North America, breeds in Canada and northern United States, winters in Mexico and Central America
039.Least_Flycatcher.size: Length: 12-14 cm, Wingspan: 19-22 cm, Weight: 8-12 g
039.Least_Flycatcher.behavior: Migratory. Sits on perch and sallies out to catch insects. Sings 'che-bek' song.

040.Olive_sided_Flycatcher.description: Large flycatcher with dark olive-gray upperparts, white underparts with dark sides, and white tufts on back.
040.Olive_sided_Flycatcher.distribution: North America, breeds in Canada and western United States, winters in South America
040.Olive_sided_Flycatcher.size: Length: 18-20 cm, Wingspan: 30-33 cm, Weight: 28-40 g
040.Olive_sided_Flycatcher.behavior: Migratory. Sits on high perch. Sings 'quick-three-beers' song.

041.Scissor_tailed_Flycatcher.description: Medium-sized flycatcher with gray head, white underparts, salmon-pink sides, and very long forked tail.
041.Scissor_tailed_Flycatcher.habitat: Open areas, grasslands, and agricultural fields
041.Scissor_tailed_Flycatcher.distribution: Central and southern United States, winters in Central America
041.Scissor_tailed_Flycatcher.size: Length: 28-38 cm (including tail), Wingspan: 38-41 cm, Weight: 30-43 g
041.Scissor_tailed_Flycatcher.behavior: Migratory. Performs aerial displays. Nests in trees or shrubs.

042.Vermilion_Flycatcher.description: Small flycatcher. Males are bright red with dark brown back and wings. Females are brown with red underparts.
042.Vermilion_Flycatcher.habitat: Open areas, grasslands, and desert scrub
042.Vermilion_Flycatcher.distribution: Southwestern United States, Mexico, and Central and South America
042.Vermilion_Flycatcher.size: Length: 13-14 cm, Wingspan: 25-27 cm, Weight: 11-14 g
042.Vermilion_Flycatcher.behavior: Year-round resident in many areas. Performs aerial displays. Nests in trees.

043.Yellow_bellied_Flycatcher.description: Small flycatcher with olive-green upperparts, yellow underparts, and two white wing bars.
043.Yellow_bellied_Flycatcher.habitat: Coniferous and mixed forests, especially bogs
043.Yellow_bellied_Flycatcher.distribution: North America, breeds in Canada and northern United States, winters in Central America
043.Yellow_bellied_Flycatcher.size: Length: 13-15 cm, Wingspan: 20-23 cm, Weight: 11-14 g
043.Yellow_bellied_Flycatcher.behavior: Migratory. Secretive. Sits on low perch. Nests on ground in moss.

044.Frigatebird.description: Very large seabird with black body, long pointed wings, deeply forked tail, and red throat pouch (males).
044.Frigatebird.distribution: Tropical oceans worldwide, breeds on islands
044.Frigatebird.size: Length: 89-114 cm, Wingspan: 217-244 cm, Weight: 1.0-1.6 kg
044.Frigatebird.diet: Fish, caught from surface or stolen from other birds
044.Frigatebird.behavior: Pirates food from other seabirds. Excellent flier. Nests in colonies on islands.

045.Northern_Fulmar.description: Medium-sized seabird with gray and white plumage, thick bill, and tube-like nostrils.
045.Northern_Fulmar.distribution: North Atlantic and North Pacific, breeds on cliffs
045.Northern_Fulmar.size: Length: 43-52 cm, Wingspan: 102-112 cm, Weight: 450-1000 g
045.Northern_Fulmar.behavior: Spends most of life at sea. Returns to land only to breed. Defends nest by spitting oil.

046.Gadwall.description: Medium-sized dabbling duck. Males are gray with black rear, white speculum. Females are mottled brown.
046.Gadwall.size: Length: 46-56 cm, Wingspan: 78-90 cm, Weight: 0.5-1.1 kg
046.Gadwall.diet: Aquatic plants, seeds, and small invertebrates
046.Gadwall.behavior: Dabbling duck. Migratory. Forms flocks in winter.

047.American_Goldfinch.description: Small finch. Breeding males are bright yellow with black cap, wings, and tail. Females and winter males are duller, olive-brown with yellow highlights.
047.American_Goldfinch.habitat: Weedy fields, open woodlands, gardens, parks, and roadsides
047.American_Goldfinch.distribution: Throughout North America, from southern Canada to northern Mexico
047.American_Goldfinch.size: Length: 11-13 cm, Wingspan: 19-22 cm, Weight: 11-20 g
047.American_Goldfinch.diet: Primarily seeds, especially from thistles, sunflowers, and dandelions. Also eats some insects during breeding season.
047.American_Goldfinch.behavior: Late breeder, nests in mid-summer when seeds are abundant. Flocks in winter. Bouncy, undulating flight pattern. Visits bird feeders for nyjer and sunflower seeds.

048.European_Goldfinch.description: Small finch with red face, black and white head, brown back, and yellow wing patches.
048.European_Goldfinch.habitat: Open woodlands, gardens, parks, and agricultural areas
048.European_Goldfinch.distribution: Europe, North Africa, and western Asia. Introduced to Australia and New Zealand
048.European_Goldfinch.size: Length: 12-13 cm, Wingspan: 21-25 cm, Weight: 14-19 g
048.European_Goldfinch.diet: Seeds, especially thistle and teasel seeds
048.European_Goldfinch.behavior: Social, forms flocks. Visits bird feeders. Beautiful song.

049.Boat_tailed_Grackle.description: Large blackbird with long tail, iridescent black plumage, and yellow eyes.
049.Boat_tailed_Grackle.habitat: Coastal marshes, wetlands, and urban areas
049.Boat_tailed_Grackle.size: Length: 37-43 cm, Wingspan: 39-50 cm, Weight: 165-250 g
049.Boat_tailed_Grackle.diet: Insects, seeds, grains, and human food scraps
049.Boat_tailed_Grackle.behavior: Year-round resident. Forms large flocks. Nests in colonies.

050.Eared_Grebe.description: Small grebe with black head and neck, golden ear tufts in breeding season, and red eyes.
050.Eared_Grebe.distribution: North America, breeds in western United States and Canada, winters in southwestern United States and Mexico
050.Eared_Grebe.size: Length: 28-34 cm, Wingspan: 55-60 cm, Weight: 250-400 g
050.Eared_Grebe.diet: Aquatic insects, small fish, and crustaceans
050.Eared_Grebe.behavior: Migratory. Excellent diver. Forms large flocks in winter.

051.Horned_Grebe.description: Small grebe with black head, golden ear tufts, red eyes, and chestnut neck in breeding season.
051.Horned_Grebe.distribution: North America, breeds in Canada and Alaska, winters in coastal United States
051.Horned_Grebe.size: Length: 31-38 cm, Wingspan: 55-60 cm, Weight: 300-570 g
051.Horned_Grebe.diet: Aquatic insects, small fish, and crustaceans
051.Horned_Grebe.behavior: Migratory. Excellent diver. Nests on floating vegetation.

052.Pied_billed_Grebe.description: Small grebe with brown body, black ring around bill in breeding season, and short tail.
052.Pied_billed_Grebe.size: Length: 30-38 cm, Wingspan: 45-55 cm, Weight: 250-600 g
052.Pied_billed_Grebe.diet: Aquatic insects, small fish, and crustaceans
052.Pied_billed_Grebe.behavior: Year-round resident in many areas. Excellent diver. Builds floating nest.

053.Western_Grebe.description: Large grebe with long neck, black cap, white face and neck, and red eyes.
053.Western_Grebe.distribution: Western North America, breeds in western United States and Canada, winters along Pacific Coast
053.Western_Grebe.size: Length: 55-75 cm, Wingspan: 79-102 cm, Weight: 800-1800 g
053.Western_Grebe.behavior: Migratory. Performs elaborate courtship displays. Nests in colonies.

054.Blue_Grosbeak.description: Medium-sized songbird. Males are deep blue with chestnut wing bars. Females are brown with blue tinges.
054.Blue_Grosbeak.habitat: Brushy areas, open woodlands, and fields
054.Blue_Grosbeak.distribution: Southern and central United States, winters in Mexico and Central America
054.Blue_Grosbeak.size: Length: 14-19 cm, Wingspan: 26-29 cm, Weight: 26-31 g
054.Blue_Grosbeak.behavior: Migratory. Sings beautiful song. Nests in shrubs.

172.Nashville_Warbler.description: Small warbler with olive upperparts, yellow underparts, gray head, and white eye ring.
172.Nashville_Warbler.distribution: North America, breeds in Canada and northern United States, winters in Mexico and Central America
172.Nashville_Warbler.size: Length: 11-13 cm, Wingspan: 18-20 cm, Weight: 7-11 g
172.Nashville_Warbler.behavior: Migratory. Forages in trees. Nests on ground.

173.Orange_crowned_Warbler.description: Small warbler with olive-yellow upperparts, yellow underparts, and faint orange crown patch.
173.Orange_crowned_Warbler.distribution: North America, breeds in Canada and western United States, winters in southern United States, Mexico, and Central America
173.Orange_crowned_Warbler.size: Length: 12-13 cm, Wingspan: 19-21 cm, Weight: 7-11 g
173.Orange_crowned_Warbler.behavior: Migratory. Visits feeders for suet. Nests on ground or low in shrubs.

174.Palm_Warbler.description: Small warbler with brown cap, yellow underparts with streaks, and constantly bobs tail.
174.Palm_Warbler.distribution: North America, breeds in Canada, winters in southeastern United States, Caribbean, and Central America
174.Palm_Warbler.size: Length: 12-14 cm, Wingspan: 20-22 cm, Weight: 9-14 g
174.Palm_Warbler.behavior: Migratory. Constantly bobs tail. Forages on ground.

175.Pine_Warbler.description: Small warbler with olive-yellow upperparts, yellow underparts with faint streaks, and white wing bars.
175.Pine_Warbler.distribution: Eastern and southeastern United States, year-round resident in many areas
175.Pine_Warbler.size: Length: 12-14 cm, Wingspan: 20-23 cm, Weight: 9-15 g
175.Pine_Warbler.behavior: Year-round resident in many areas. Visits feeders for suet. Nests in pine trees.

176.Prairie_Warbler.description: Small warbler with olive upperparts, yellow underparts with black streaks, and chestnut streaks on back.
176.Prairie_Warbler.habitat: Shrubby areas, pine barrens, and young forests
176.Prairie_Warbler.distribution: Eastern United States, winters in Caribbean and Central America
176.Prairie_Warbler.size: Length: 11-12 cm, Wingspan: 18-19 cm, Weight: 6-9 g
176.Prairie_Warbler.behavior: Migratory. Constantly bobs tail. Nests in shrubs.

177.Prothonotary_Warbler.description: Medium-sized warbler with bright yellow head and underparts, blue-gray wings, and olive back.
177.Prothonotary_Warbler.distribution: Eastern and central United States, winters in Central America and Caribbean
177.Prothonotary_Warbler.size: Length: 13-14 cm, Wingspan: 20-22 cm, Weight: 12-15 g
177.Prothonotary_Warbler.behavior: Migratory. Nests in tree cavities. Only eastern warbler that nests in cavities.

178.Swainson_Warbler.description: Medium-sized warbler with brown upperparts, white underparts, and brown crown stripe.
178.Swainson_Warbler.habitat: Dense undergrowth in bottomland forests and swamps
178.Swainson_Warbler.distribution: Southeastern United States, winters in Caribbean and Central America
178.Swainson_Warbler.size: Length: 13-14 cm, Wingspan: 20-22 cm, Weight: 15-19 g
178.Swainson_Warbler.behavior: Migratory. Very secretive. Skulks on ground. Nests on ground.

179.Tennessee_Warbler.description: Small warbler with olive upperparts, white underparts, gray head, and white eyebrow stripe.
179.Tennessee_Warbler.distribution: North America, breeds in Canada and Alaska, winters in Central and South America
179.Tennessee_Warbler.size: Length: 11-13 cm, Wingspan: 19-20 cm, Weight: 8-11 g
179.Tennessee_Warbler.diet: Insects, especially spruce budworms, and fruits
179.Tennessee_Warbler.behavior: Migratory. Forages in trees. Nests on ground.

180.Wilson_Warbler.description: Small warbler with olive upperparts, yellow underparts, and black cap (males) or olive cap (females).
180.Wilson_Warbler.habitat: Dense undergrowth in forests and shrublands
180.Wilson_Warbler.distribution: North America, breeds in Canada and Alaska, winters in Mexico and Central America
180.Wilson_Warbler.size: Length: 10-12 cm, Wingspan: 16-18 cm, Weight: 5-10 g
180.Wilson_Warbler.behavior: Migratory. Constantly flicks tail. Nests on ground.

181.Worm_eating_Warbler.description: Medium-sized warbler with olive upperparts, buff underparts, and black and buff striped head.
181.Worm_eating_Warbler.distribution: Eastern United States, winters in Caribbean and Central America
181.Worm_eating_Warbler.size: Length: 13 cm, Wingspan: 20-22 cm, Weight: 11-15 g
181.Worm_eating_Warbler.behavior: Migratory. Skulks on ground. Nests on ground in dense vegetation.

182.Yellow_Warbler.description: Small warbler. Males are bright yellow with reddish streaks on breast. Females are duller yellow.
182.Yellow_Warbler.distribution: North America, breeds in United States and Canada, winters in Central and South America
182.Yellow_Warbler.size: Length: 12-13 cm, Wingspan: 16-20 cm, Weight: 7-16 g
182.Yellow_Warbler.behavior: Migratory. Sings sweet 'sweet-sweet-sweet' song. Nests in shrubs or trees.

183.Northern_Waterthrush.description: Large warbler with brown upperparts, white underparts with dark streaks, and white eyebrow stripe.
183.Northern_Waterthrush.distribution: North America, breeds in Canada and Alaska, winters in Central America, Caribbean, and northern South America
183.Northern_Waterthrush.size: Length: 12-15 cm, Wingspan: 21-24 cm, Weight: 13-25 g
183.Northern_Waterthrush.behavior: Migratory. Walks along water edges. Constantly bobs tail. Nests on ground.

184.Louisiana_Waterthrush.description: Large warbler with brown upperparts, white underparts with dark streaks, and white eyebrow stripe.
184.Louisiana_Waterthrush.distribution: Eastern North America, breeds in United States, winters in Central America and Caribbean
184.Louisiana_Waterthrush.size: Length: 14-16 cm, Wingspan: 21-25 cm, Weight: 14-28 g
184.Louisiana_Waterthrush.behavior: Migratory. Walks along stream banks. Nests on ground near water.

185.Bohemian_Waxwing.description: Medium-sized songbird similar to Cedar Waxwing but larger, with gray belly and white wing patches.
185.Bohemian_Waxwing.habitat: Coniferous forests and open areas with fruit trees
185.Bohemian_Waxwing.distribution: Northern North America, breeds in Alaska and Canada, winters in northern United States
185.Bohemian_Waxwing.size: Length: 19-21 cm, Wingspan: 32-35 cm, Weight: 50-60 g
185.Bohemian_Waxwing.behavior: Irruptive migrant. Forms large flocks. Visits berry trees.

186.Cedar_Waxwing.description: Medium-sized songbird with sleek brown body, yellow-tipped tail, red waxy wing tips, and black mask.
186.Cedar_Waxwing.habitat: Open woodlands, parks, and gardens with fruit trees
186.Cedar_Waxwing.distribution: North America, breeds in Canada and northern United States, winters throughout United States and Mexico
186.Cedar_Waxwing.size: Length: 14-17 cm, Wingspan: 22-30 cm, Weight: 30-40 g
186.Cedar_Waxwing.behavior: Social, forms large flocks. Visits berry trees. Passes berries to each other.

187.American_Three_toed_Woodpecker.description: Medium-sized woodpecker with black and white barred back, yellow crown patch (males), and three toes.
187.American_Three_toed_Woodpecker.distribution: North America, breeds in Canada and Alaska, winters in northern United States
187.American_Three_toed_Woodpecker.size: Length: 20-23 cm, Wingspan: 35-38 cm, Weight: 50-70 g
187.American_Three_toed_Woodpecker.diet: Bark beetles and other wood-boring insects
187.American_Three_toed_Woodpecker.behavior: Year-round resident in many areas. Forages on dead and dying trees.

188.Pileated_Woodpecker.description: Very large woodpecker with black body, white stripes on face, and red crest. Males have red mustache.
188.Pileated_Woodpecker.distribution: North America, from Canada to southeastern United States
188.Pileated_Woodpecker.size: Length: 40-49 cm, Wingspan: 66-75 cm, Weight: 250-350 g
188.Pileated_Woodpecker.diet: Carpenter ants, wood-boring beetles, fruits, and nuts
188.Pileated_Woodpecker.behavior: Year-round resident. Creates large rectangular holes in trees. Loud call.

189.Red_bellied_Woodpecker.description: Medium-sized woodpecker with black and white barred back, red cap and nape, and pale belly.
189.Red_bellied_Woodpecker.habitat: Deciduous and mixed forests, parks, and gardens
189.Red_bellied_Woodpecker.distribution: Eastern and central United States, year-round resident
189.Red_bellied_Woodpecker.size: Length: 22-26 cm, Wingspan: 38-46 cm, Weight: 56-91 g
189.Red_bellied_Woodpecker.behavior: Year-round resident. Visits bird feeders. Stores food in bark crevices.

190.Red_cockaded_Woodpecker.description: Medium-sized woodpecker with black and white barred back, white cheek patches, and small red spot on head (males).
190.Red_cockaded_Woodpecker.size: Length: 18-23 cm, Wingspan: 35-41 cm, Weight: 40-50 g
190.Red_cockaded_Woodpecker.behavior: Endangered species. Cooperative breeder. Nests in living pine trees.

191.Red_headed_Woodpecker.description: Medium-sized woodpecker with entirely red head, black and white body, and white wing patches.
191.Red_headed_Woodpecker.habitat: Open woodlands, parks, and areas with dead trees
191.Red_headed_Woodpecker.size: Length: 19-23 cm, Wingspan: 42 cm, Weight: 56-97 g
191.Red_headed_Woodpecker.behavior: Stores food in tree cavities. Declining population. Nests in dead trees.

192.Downy_Woodpecker.description: Small woodpecker with black and white plumage, white back, and small bill. Males have red nape patch.
192.Downy_Woodpecker.distribution: North America, from Alaska to Mexico
192.Downy_Woodpecker.size: Length: 14-18 cm, Wingspan: 25-30 cm, Weight: 20-33 g
192.Downy_Woodpecker.behavior: Year-round resident. Visits bird feeders. Drums on trees. Nests in tree cavities.

193.Bewick_Wren.description: Small wren with brown upperparts, white underparts, and long tail with white corners.
193.Bewick_Wren.distribution: Western and central North America, year-round resident in many areas
193.Bewick_Wren.size: Length: 13 cm, Wingspan: 18 cm, Weight: 8-12 g
193.Bewick_Wren.behavior: Year-round resident in many areas. Very vocal. Nests in cavities.

194.Cactus_Wren.description: Large wren with brown upperparts with white spots, white underparts with dark spots, and long tail.
194.Cactus_Wren.habitat: Desert scrub and arid areas with cacti
194.Cactus_Wren.size: Length: 18-22 cm, Wingspan: 28-30 cm, Weight: 33-47 g
194.Cactus_Wren.behavior: Year-round resident. Builds large domed nests in cacti. Very vocal.

195.Carolina_Wren.description: Large wren with reddish-brown upperparts, buff underparts, and white eyebrow stripe.
195.Carolina_Wren.habitat: Dense vegetation, woodlands, gardens, and parks
195.Carolina_Wren.distribution: Eastern and southeastern United States, year-round resident
195.Carolina_Wren.size: Length: 12-14 cm, Wingspan: 29 cm, Weight: 18-22 g
195.Carolina_Wren.behavior: Year-round resident. Loud 'tea-kettle' song. Pairs stay together year-round. Nests in various cavities.

196.House_Wren.description: Small, brown wren with barred wings and tail. Short, slightly curved bill.
196.House_Wren.habitat: Open woodlands, gardens, parks, and suburban areas
196.House_Wren.size: Length: 11-13 cm, Wingspan: 15 cm, Weight: 10-12 g
196.House_Wren.behavior: Very vocal, sings complex songs. Nests in cavities, including nest boxes. Aggressive towards other cavity nesters.

197.Marsh_Wren.description: Small wren with brown upperparts with white streaks, white underparts, and short tail.
197.Marsh_Wren.habitat: Marshes and wetlands with dense vegetation
197.Marsh_Wren.distribution: North America, breeds in Canada and United States, winters in southern United States and Mexico
197.Marsh_Wren.size: Length: 10-14 cm, Wingspan: 15 cm, Weight: 9-14 g
197.Marsh_Wren.behavior: Migratory in northern range. Very vocal. Builds domed nests in marsh vegetation.

198.Rock_Wren.description: Medium-sized wren with gray-brown upperparts, buff underparts, and long tail.
198.Rock_Wren.distribution: Western North America, from Canada to Mexico
198.Rock_Wren.size: Length: 14-16 cm, Wingspan: 20-22 cm, Weight: 14-18 g
198.Rock_Wren.behavior: Year-round resident in many areas. Nests in rock crevices. Constantly bobs.

199.Winter_Wren.description: Very small wren with brown mottled upperparts, buff underparts, and short tail.
199.Winter_Wren.distribution: North America, breeds in Canada and northern United States, winters in southern United States
199.Winter_Wren.size: Length: 9-10 cm, Wingspan: 13-15 cm, Weight: 8-12 g
199.Winter_Wren.behavior: Migratory. Very secretive. Sings loud, complex song. Nests in cavities.

200.Common_Yellowthroat.description: Small warbler. Males have black mask, yellow throat, and olive back. Females lack mask.
200.Common_Yellowthroat.distribution: North America, breeds throughout United States and Canada, winters in southern United States, Mexico, and Central America
200.Common_Yellowthroat.size: Length: 11-14 cm, Wingspan: 15-19 cm, Weight: 8-11 g
200.Common_Yellowthroat.behavior: Migratory. Skulks in dense vegetation. Sings 'wichity-wichity' song.
